Why Machine Learning?

  • Classical Statistics relies on assumptions:
  1. Choose a model for the underlying law governing the observed phenomenon;
  2. Use statistical tools to estimate unknown parameters;
  3. Make predictions;
  • However:
  • Assumption is wrong \(\Rightarrow\) parameters estimates make no sense;
  • Make prediction poorly;
  • You might say: Ok lets choose a better hypothesis!
  • There are a lot number of possible families of distributions;
  • But what if the data has a huge number of features? How do we visualize this data to make a model proposition?
  • The stage of modelisation is the most difficult part;
  • In a nutshel: You can end up with poor \(\hat{f}(X)\);

Why Machine Learning?

  • What if I told you there might be a better data-driven approach?
  • and this data-driven approach will try to find appropriate transformation?

  • and this endeavor will be guided by a learning process?
  • and all this process wil be done by a computer (algorithm)?
  • Thats Machine Learning:
  1. a searching for useful representations of input data;
  2. within an enhanced space of possibilities;
  3. using guidance from a feedback signal;

Supervised vs Unsupervised Learning

  • Supervised or Unsupervised;
  • Supervised:
    • For each obs of the predictor measurement(s) \(x_i\), there is a reponse \(y_i\);
    • The vast majority of ML applications are supervised;
  • Unsupervised is more challenging:
    • for each obs \(i = 1, ..., n\), we do not observe \(y_i\);
    • examples: cluster analysis;
  • Semi-supervised:
    • For \(m\) of the observations, where \(m < n\), we have both \(x\) and \(y\);
    • For \(n - m\) we have the \(x\) and do not have the \(y\);
    • Cluster the \(n\) obs into \(k\) distinct groups;
    • Use the labels for the \(m\) obs in this \(k\) groups to label the remaining ones.

Regression vs Classification

  • Variables can be characterized as quantitative and qualitative;
  • Quantitative:
    • Take on numerical values;
    • ex: sales, income, value of a house, price of a stock;
    • linear model;
  • Qualitative:
    • Take on values in one of \(K\) different categories;
    • ex: poverty, gender, default on debt, customer churn;
    • logistic/probit models;

Bias-variance trade-off

  • ML give us access for broader range of possibilities;
  • Why not just presenting the best one algorithm?

There is no free lunch here!

  • On a particular dataset one algorithm may work best, but some other method on a different dataset;
  • How do we define best?
  • In general:

    • for regression setting \[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i = 1}^N (y_i - \hat{f}(x_i))^2 \]

    • for classification setting: \[ \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i = 1}^N I(y_i \neq \hat{y_i}) \]

  • We (almost) do not care about train performance;
  • Important to have great performance on unseen (test) set;

  • High train performance, low test performance \(\Rightarrow\) overfitting;
  • Our algorithim is working too hard and may be picking random pattern (\(\epsilon\)); \[ Y = f(X) + \epsilon \]
  • It can be shown, the expected error can be decomposed as:

\[ E\left(y_0 - \hat{f}(x_0)\right)^2 = Var\left(\hat{f}(x_0)\right) + \left[Bias\left(\hat{f}(x_0)\right)\right]^2 + Var(\epsilon) \]

\[ E\left(y_0 - \hat{f}(x_0)\right)^2 = Var\left(\hat{f}(x_0)\right) + \left[Bias\left(\hat{f}(x_0)\right)\right]^2 + Var(\epsilon) \]

  • Variance refers to amount by which \(\hat{f}\) would change if training set changes;
    • In general, more flexible ML methods have higher variance;
  • Bias refer to the error: \(y_o - \hat{f}(x_0)\)
    • In general, more flexible ML methods have lower bias;
  • As a general rule: as we use more flexible algorithms:

Variance \(\uparrow\) and Bias \(\downarrow\)

  • The ultimate goal:

Finding an algorithm for which both (variance and bias) are low!

Algorithms - Part 01

The Bayes Classifier

  • The Bayes Theorem states that

\[ P(y/X) = \frac{P(X/y)P(y)}{P(X)} \]

  • The variable \(Y\) is the class variable and \(X\) represent \(p\) parameters/features;

\[ P(y/X_1, ..., X_p) = \frac{P(X_1/y)...P(X_p/y)P(Y)}{P(X_1)...P(X_p)} \]

  • Notice that for each \(X\), the denominator does not change;

\[ P(y/X_1, ..., X_p) \propto P(X_1/y)...P(X_p/y)P(Y) \]

  • Therefore, we need to find the class \(y\) for each \[ argmax_y \quad P(Y)\prod_{i=1}^pP(X_i/y) \]
  • It can be shown that the solution yields to the lowest test error, called the Bayes error rate;

Bayes Classifier

  • In theory we would love to predict qualitative \(Y\) using the Bayes classifier;
  • In the real world, conditional distribution of \(Y\) given \(X\) is unknown;
  • Hence, the Bayes Classifier serves as unattainable gold standard;
  • Many approaches attempt to estimate the conditional distribution;

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

  • Suppose we want to classify an obs into K classes (K \(\ge\) 2);
  • Let \(\pi_k\) prior probability for the \(k_{th}\) class;
  • Let \(f_k(X) = \text{P}(X = x/Y = k)\) the density funcion;
  • Instead of computing \(\text{P}(Y = k/X = x)\), compute \(\pi_k\) and \(f_k(X)\);
  • Problem: estimate \(f_k(X)\) is challenging.

LDA

  1. In order to estimate \(f_k(X)\), assume is Gaussian;
  1. Assume that \(\sigma_1^2 = \sigma_2^2 = ... = \sigma_K^2 = \sigma^2\);
  • Using (1) and (2):

\[ \text{p}_k(X) =\frac{ \pi_k \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma} \text{exp}\left(- \frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x - \mu_k)^2\right)}{ \sum_{l = 1}^K \pi_l \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma} \text{exp}\left(- \frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x - \mu_l)^2\right)} \]

  • Rule: assign an observation with \(X = x\) where \(\text{p}_k(X)\) is largest.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

  • LDA assumes multivariate Gaussian distribution;
  1. QDA also assumes multivariate Gaussian distribution;
  1. However, each class has its own covariance matrix:

\[ X \sim \mathcal{N}\left(\mu_k, \Sigma_k\right) \]

  • Using (1) and (2):

\[ \text{p}_k(X) =\frac{ \pi_k \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_k^2}} \text{exp}\left(- \frac{1}{2\sigma_k^2}(x - \mu_k)^2\right)}{ \sum_{l = 1}^K \pi_l \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_l^2}} \text{exp}\left(- \frac{1}{2\sigma_l^2}(x - \mu_l)^2\right)} \]

LDA vs QDA?

  • Answer: bias variance trade-off;

  • LDA : less flexible (more bias), but less variance;

  • QDA : more flexible (less bias), but more variance;

  • LDA tends to be better if there is few training: reduce variance is critical;

  • QDA is recomended if training set is very large and common variance assumption is untenable.

K-Nearest Neighbors

  • Another attempt to estimate the distribution of \(Y\) given \(X\);
  • Let \(K\) be a positive integer and a test obs \(x_0\);
  • KNN identifies \(K\) points in the traning data that are closest to \(x_0\) represented by \(\mathcal{N}_0\);
  • It estimates the conditional probability for class \(j\) as \[ P(Y = j/X = x_0) = \frac{1}{K} \sum_{i \in \mathcal{N}_0} I(y_i = j) \]
  • Finally, KNN classifies the test obs \(x_0\) to the class with largest probability;

KNN

  • The choice of \(K\) has a drastic effect on the KNN classifier;
  • As \(K\) grows, the method becomes less flexible and produce decision boundary close to linear;
  • This correspond to a low-variance but high-bias classifier;

Penalized methods

  • A simple machine learning model familiar to us: linear model:

\[ Y = X\beta + \epsilon \]

  • Remember that we choose the parameter vector \(\beta \in \mathcal{R}^P\) such as \[ \hat{\beta}^{OLS} = argmin_{\beta} \quad \sum_{i}^N(Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 \]
  • The solution yields to \(\hat{\beta}^{OLS} = (X^TX)^{-1}X^TY\);
  • When \(N > P\), this solution is well defined;
  • However, when \(P\) is large, OLS solution is at risk of overfitting;
  • Worse: if \(P \gt N\), there is no longer a unique solution and variance is tends to infinity;
  • Solution: by shrinking (penalizing) the estimated coefficients, we can reduce the variance at the cost of a negligible increase in bias.

Penalized methods

  • These approaches involve fitting a model involving all \(P\) predictors, even for \(P > N\);
  • However, the estimated coefficients are shrunken towards zero relative to the OLS estimates;
  • This shrinkage has the effect of reducing variance;
  • Depending on what type of shrinkage, some of the coefficients may be estimated to be exactly zero;

  • The best-known techniques for shrinking the coefficients are:
    • Ridge;
    • LASSO;
    • Elastic net.

Penalized methods: Ridge

  • Recall that OLS estimates \(\hat{\beta}^{OLS}\) by minimizing \[ \text{RSS} = \sum_{i=1}^N (Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 \]
  • Ridge algorithm will estimate \(\hat{\beta}^{ridge}\) by minimizing

\[ \sum_{i=1}^N (Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 + \lambda\sum_{j=1}^P \beta_j^2 \\ \text{RSS} + \lambda\sum_{j=1}^P \beta_j^2 \]

  • where \(\lambda\) is a tunning parameter;
  • Unlike least squares, ridge regression will produce a different \(\hat{\beta}^{ridge}\) for each value of \(\lambda\);
  • Selecting a good value for \(\lambda\) is critical.

Penalized methods: LASSO

  • The Ridge algorithm will include all \(P\) predictors in the final model;
  • The penalty \(\lambda \sum_{i=1}^N \beta^2\) will shrink all of the coefficients towards zero;
  • the LASSO algorithm will estimate \(\hat{\beta}^{LASSO}\) by minimizing

\[ \sum_{i=1}^N (Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^P |\beta_j| \\ \text{RSS} + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^P |\beta_j| \]

  • As with Ridge algorithm, the LASSO shrinks the coefficient estimates towards zero;
  • However, the \(l_1\) penalty has the effect of forcing some of the coefficient estimates to be exactly zero;
  • Hence, the LASSO yields sparse models.

Another formulation for Ridge and LASSO

  • One can show that \(\hat{\beta}^{ridge}\) and \(\hat{\beta}^{LASSO}\) solve the following problems

\[ \hat{\beta}^{ridge} = argmin_{\beta} \, \sum_{i=1}^N (Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 \\ \text{subject to} \quad \sum_{j=1}^P \beta_j^2 \le s \]

\[ \hat{\beta}^{LASSO} = argmin_{\beta} \, \sum_{i=1}^N (Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 \\ \text{subject to} \quad \sum_{j=1}^P |\beta_j| \le s \]

  • In other words, for every value of \(\lambda\), there is some \(s\) such that will give the \(\hat{\beta}^{ridge}\) and \(\hat{\beta}^{LASSO}\);

Another formulation for Ridge and LASSO

Penalized methods: Elastic net

  • Elastic net is an algorithm which involves the \(l_1\) and \(l_2\) penalty norms;
  • This algorithm method aims to overcome some limitations of the LASSO;
  • For instance, if there is a group of highly correlated variables, then the LASSO tends to select one variable;
  • The estimates from the elastic net method are defined by

\[ \hat{\beta}^{EN} = argmin_\beta \sum_{i=1}^N (Y_i - X_i^T\beta)^2 + \lambda \left[ \left(\frac{1 - \alpha}{2}\right) \sum_{j=1}^P (\beta_j)^2 + \alpha \sum_{j=1}^P |\beta_j|\right] \]

  • Where \(\alpha\) and \(\lambda\) are tunning parameters;
  • The quadratic penalty term makes the loss function strictly convex, and it therefore has a unique minimum;
  • The elastic net method includes the LASSO and ridge algorithm.
